# Task_03 – Verilog RTL Design of Sequential Circuits and Flip-Flops

## Objective

This project demonstrates the design and simulation of fundamental sequential circuits using Verilog HDL. The objective is to understand clock-driven digital systems, memory elements, and sequential logic behavior through the implementation of Flip-Flops, Registers, and Counters.

---

## Tools Used

* Verilog HDL
* EDA Playground
* Icarus Verilog
* GTKWave
* ModelSim (Optional)

---

## Sequential Circuits Implemented

### 1. D Flip-Flop

A D Flip-Flop stores a single bit of data and transfers the input value to the output on the rising edge of the clock signal.

#### Features

* Edge-triggered operation
* Stores one-bit data
* Synchronous sequential circuit

---

### 2. JK Flip-Flop

A JK Flip-Flop is an enhanced flip-flop that eliminates the invalid state found in SR Flip-Flops.

#### Operations

| J | K | Q(next)   |
| - | - | --------- |
| 0 | 0 | No Change |
| 0 | 1 | Reset     |
| 1 | 0 | Set       |
| 1 | 1 | Toggle    |

---

### 3. 4-Bit Register

A register stores multiple bits of data using flip-flops.

#### Features

* 4-bit data storage
* Clock-driven operation
* Parallel data transfer

---

### 4. 4-Bit Binary Counter

A counter increments its value on every positive clock edge.

#### Features

* Counts from 0000 to 1111
* Automatic rollover
* Sequential counting operation

---

## Testbench Development

Separate testbenches were created for verifying the functionality of each sequential circuit.

### Verification Performed

* Clock generation
* Input stimulus application
* Output monitoring
* Functional validation

---

## Simulation Results

The designs were simulated using Verilog simulation tools and analyzed using waveform viewers.

### Observations

* Output changes only on the clock edge.
* D Flip-Flop correctly follows input data.
* JK Flip-Flop performs Set, Reset, Hold, and Toggle operations.
* Register stores and updates multi-bit data correctly.
* Counter increments sequentially with each clock pulse.

